04128nam a22005415i 9780804784665DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047846657 a10.1515/97808047846652doi  a(DE-B1597)563837  a(OCoLC)1198930703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN744b.C3613 2012 7aLIT0041702bisacsh04a809.93384a809/.933841 aCampe, Rüdiger, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Game of Probability :bLiterature and Calculation from Pascal to Kleist /cRüdiger Campe. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (504 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Theology and the Law -- t2. Numbers and Calculation in Context -- t3. Writing the Calculation of Chances -- t4. Probability, a Postscript to the Theory of Chance -- t5. Probability Applied -- t6. Continued Proclamations -- t7. Defoe's Robinson Crusoe, or, The Improbability of Survival -- t8. Numbers and Tables in Narration -- t9. Novels and Tables -- t10. The Theory of Probability and the Form of the Novel -- t11. "Improbable Probability" -- t12. The Appearance of Truth -- t13. "Probable" or "Plausible" -- t14. Kleist's "Improbable Veracities," or, A Romantic Ending -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThere exist literary histories of probability and scientific histories of probability, but it has generally been thought that the two did not meet. Campe begs to differ. Mathematical probability, he argues, took over the role of the old probability of poets, orators, and logicians, albeit in scientific terms. Indeed, mathematical probability would not even have been possible without the other probability, whose roots lay in classical antiquity. The Game of Probability revisits the seventeenth and eighteenth-century "probabilistic revolution," providing a history of the relations between mathematical and rhetorical techniques, between the scientific and the aesthetic. This was a revolution that overthrew the "order of things," notably the way that science and art positioned themselves with respect to reality, and its participants included a wide variety of people from as many walks of life. Campe devotes chapters to them in turn. Focusing on the interpretation of games of chance as the model for probability and on the reinterpretation of aesthetic form as verisimilitude (a critical question for theoreticians of that new literary genre, the novel), the scope alone of Campe's book argues for probability's crucial role in the constitution of modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEuropean literaturey17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEuropean literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aProbability in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh1 aWiggins, Ellwood08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478466540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804784665423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804784665.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles